ewish religious law, or halakha, and shari‘a law.An illuminating work on a topic of vital relevance today, Jews and the Qur’an offers a nuanced understanding of Islam’s engagement with Judaism in the time of Muhammad and his followers, and serves as a needed corrective to common misperceptions about Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIslamxRelationsxJudaism. 0aJews in the Qurʼan. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Koran & Sacred Writings.2bisacsh  aAbraham Geiger.  aArab world.  aArabic name.  aArabic.  aArabs.  aBanu Nadir.  aBanu Qurayza.  aBathsheba.  aBatin (Islam).  aBerakhot (Talmud).  aBible.  aBook of Deuteronomy.  aBook of Exodus.  aBook of Leviticus.  aChristianity and Judaism.  aConversion to Judaism.  aCrucifixion of Jesus.  aDepictions of Muhammad.  aEarly Muslim conquests.  aEpistle to the Hebrews.  aExegesis.  aEzra.  aFive Pillars of Islam.  aGehenna.  aGenesis Rabbah.  aHajj.  aHalakha.  aHarut and Marut.  aHebrew Bible.  aHebrew calendar.  aHebrew name.  aHebrews.  aIbn Hisham.  aInfidel.  aIslam.  aIslamic culture.  aIslamic–Jewish relations.  aIslamism.  aIsrael.  aIsraelites.  aJahannam.  aJerusalem Talmud.  aJewish Currents.  aJewish culture.  aJewish diaspora.  aJewish education.  aJewish history.  aJewish literature.  aJewish prayer.  aJewish religious movements.  aJews.  aJudaism.  aJudea.  aJudeo-Christian.  aKaraite Judaism.  aKashrut.  aLand of Israel.  aLives of the Prophets.  aMecca.  aMidrash.  aMishnah.  aMitzvah.  aMount Sinai.  aMuhammad's wives.  aMuhammad.  aMuslim.  aMuslims (nationality).  aNaskh (script).  aOral Torah.  aPeople of the Book.  aPhilistines.  aPolemic.  aProphetic biography.  aProphets and messengers in Islam.  aProphets of